# 📄 PDF Upload & Session-Based Text Storage — Implementation Plan (v2)

## What Changed from v1

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **v1** stored a single [text](file:///d:/Projects/education-tutor-for-remote-india/client/src/context/ThemeContext.tsx#5-9) string per session.
> **v2** stores an **array of documents** per session — users can upload multiple PDFs at once or one by one over time.

---

## 🧠 Core Data Structure Change

### ❌ Old (v1) — Single PDF per session
```typescript
Map<sessionId, { text: string, uploadedAt: number }>
```

### ✅ New (v2) — Multiple PDFs per session
```typescript
Map<sessionId, {
  documents: Array<{
    id: string,           // unique ID per document (uuid)
    fileName: string,     // "physics_ch3.pdf"
    text: string,         // extracted text from this PDF
    pageCount: number,    // number of pages
    uploadedAt: number    // timestamp
  }>,
  createdAt: number       // when session started
}>
```

### Example in Memory:
```
sessionId: "abc123" → {
  documents: [
    { id: "doc-1", fileName: "physics.pdf",  text: "Force is...",     pageCount: 45,  uploadedAt: 1710000 },
    { id: "doc-2", fileName: "chemistry.pdf", text: "Atoms are...",   pageCount: 30,  uploadedAt: 1710050 },
    { id: "doc-3", fileName: "math.pdf",      text: "Algebra is...",  pageCount: 60,  uploadedAt: 1710100 }
  ],
  createdAt: 1710000
}
```

---

## 🏗️ Architecture Diagram

```mermaid
sequenceDiagram
    participant Browser as Frontend (React)
    participant Server as Backend (Express)
    participant Memory as In-Memory Store (Map)
    participant PdfParse as pdf-parse Library

    Note over Browser: User selects 1 or more PDFs

    Browser->>Server: POST /api/upload-pdf (multipart: multiple files)
    Note right of Server: multer.array('pdfs') receives all files as Buffers

    loop For each uploaded file
        Server->>PdfParse: pdfParse(fileBuffer)
        PdfParse-->>Server: { text, numpages }
        Server->>Memory: session.documents.push({ id, fileName, text, pageCount })
    end

    Server-->>Browser: { success, documents: [{ id, fileName, pageCount }] }

    Browser->>Server: POST /api/ask { question }
    Server->>Memory: get session → combine ALL document texts
    Note right of Server: context = doc1.text + doc2.text + doc3.text
    Server-->>Browser: { answer: "..." }

    Note over Browser: User removes a specific PDF
    Browser->>Server: DELETE /api/document/:docId
    Server->>Memory: session.documents.filter(d => d.id !== docId)
    Server-->>Browser: { success, remainingDocs: [...] }
```

---

